However, formula_51 is &quot;not&quot; a variant of formula_56, since no substitution can transform the latter term into the former one.
The latter term is therefore properly more special than the former one.

For arbitrary formula_14, a term may be both more general and more special than a structurally different term.
For example, if ⊕ is idempotent, that is, if always formula_58, then the term formula_59 is more general than formula_60, and vice versa, although formula_59 and formula_60 are of different structure.

A substitution formula_43 is &quot;more special&quot; than, or &quot;subsumed&quot; by, a substitution formula_37 if formula_65 is subsumed by formula_36 for each term formula_11. We also say that formula_37 is more general than formula_43. More formally, take a nonempty infinite set formula_2 of auxiliary variables such that no equation formula_71 in the unification problem contains variables from formula_2. Then a substitution formula_43 is subsumed by another substitution formula_37 if there is a substitution formula_75 such that for all terms formula_76, formula_77.
